04186nam a22005895i 9780774865883DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748658837 a10.59962/97807748658832doi  a(DE-B1597)661749  a(OCoLC)1202734015  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1995.9.W66bB68 2021 7aLAW0430002bisacsh04a791.43/65269272231 aBouclin, Suzanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen, Film, and Law :bCinematic Representations of Female Incarceration /cSuzanne Bouclin. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b7 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tA Genre of One’s Own -- tReforming Prisons, Transforming Women: Ann Vickers -- tThe Unattainability of Reform: Caged! -- tRecuperating Exploitation: Caged Heat -- tRepresenting Incarcerated Black Women: Stranger Inside and Civil Brand -- tRepresentation and Recalibrating the WIP Genre: Orange Is the New Black -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Filmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEntertainment and profit constitute the driving force behind popular representations of women in correctional facilities. But the creative influence of film and television also generates legal meaning. The women-in-prison (WIP) genre can leave viewers feeling both empathetic toward the women portrayed in these representations and troubled about the crimes for which they have been convicted. Focusing on five exemplary WIP films and a television series – Ann Vickers, Caged, Caged Heat, Stranger Inside, Civil Brand, and Orange Is the New Black – Women, Film, and Law asks how fictional representations explore, shape, and refine beliefs about women who are incarcerated. From melodrama to exploitation, and from theatre screenings to on-demand film, television programs, and music videos, these texts bring into view the legal, economic, and political structures that criminalize women differently from men, and that target those women who are already marginalized. Women, Film, and Law convincingly argues that popular depictions of women’s imprisonment can illuminate the multiple forms of social exclusion and oppression experienced by criminalized women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrisoners in popular culture. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 0aWomen on television. 0aWomen prisoners in motion pictures. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486588340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865883/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles